My Drunk Kitchen
Genre Comedy
Created by Hannah Hart
Starring Hannah Hart
Country of origin United States
Original language(s) English
No. of seasons 3
No. of episodes 44
Production
Camera setup single-camera
Release
Original network YouTube
Picture format 480i (SDTV)
1080i (HDTV)
Audio format Stereo
Original release March 16, 2011 (2011-03-16) – present

My Drunk Kitchen is a cooking show and comedy series of short videos created and posted on YouTube by Hannah "Harto" Hart.[1][2] The series features Hart, a San Franciscan proofreader living in Los Angeles, typically attempting to cook or bake various dishes, or otherwise engaging in some food-related activity, all while imbibing large quantities of alcoholic beverages.[1] Most episodes have their own recipe, and occasionally a corresponding beverage. The series has been praised for its drunk humor, catchphrases, and the use of jump cut editing.[3][4][5]

While the second season continued featuring her drunk antics, Hannah accompanied "My Drunk Kitchen" with a series of videos titled "Coming Out".

# Title Original posting date Link
01"So. This is Me."November 23, 2012 (2012-11-23)[24]
Hannah discusses the difficulty that comes with discovering one's homosexuality.
02"Nervous"December 4, 2012 (2012-12-04)[25]
She discusses what it's like to be attracted to straight friends of the same gender.
03"Straight People"February 5, 2013 (2013-02-05)[26]
On the cusp of Valentine's Day, Hannah discusses one of her early relationships.
04"MARRIAGE!"June 26, 2013 (2013-06-26)[27]
Hannah asks her viewers what they think about marriage, and explains her views.
05"The Closet"July 10, 2013 (2013-07-10)[28]
She lists reasons why being "in the closet" is such a difficult position to be in, and how to overcome them.

Towards the end of the second season, Hannah used Indiegogo to raise $25,000 within a month in order to kick-start her roadshow, "Hello, Harto!". She successfully raised $36,000 in four hours and made plans to continue filming "My Drunk Kitchen" on the road. While the roadshow featured Hannah's comedy skits, the show was also used to attract viewers to help volunteer in local food operations.[6]

After Hannah announced her roadshow, videos were no longer formally organized into seasons.

Hannah and Hank Green, along with Grace Helbig and Mamrie Hart, cook homemade corn dogs that are made as muffins due to a lack of sticks. The episode was shot by Grace and did not use a mounted camera due to the height differences between Hannah and the others.

Hannah is hungover again and gives a small tour of her kitchen.
